# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-charger
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-charger/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of Ramblers soared in the late 1950s partly because of American Motors' focus on the compact car and its marketing efforts.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] These included sponsoring the hugely popular Walt Disney anthology television series and as an exhibitor at the Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] George Romney himself pitched the Rambler product in television commercials.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the "Big Three" introduced ever-larger cars, American Motors followed a "dinosaur-fighter" strategy.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's leadership focused the company on the compact car, a fuel-efficient vehicle 20 years before there was a real need for them.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Romney a high profile in the media.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Two core strategic factors came into play: (1) the use of shared components in American Motors products and (2) a refusal to participate in the Big Three's restyling race.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This cost-control policy helped Rambler develop a reputation for building solid economy cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Company officials were confident in the changing market and in 1959 announced a $10 million (US$110,445,205 today) expansion of its Kenosha complex (to increase annual straight-time capacity from 300,000 to 440,000 cars).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors was also beginning to experiment with non-gasoline-powered automobiles.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] On April 1, 1959, American Motors and Sonotone Corporation announced a joint research effort to consider producing an electric car that was to be powered by a "self-charging" battery.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sonotone had the technology for making sintered plate nickel–cadmium batteries that can be recharged very rapidly and are lighter than a typical automobile lead–acid battery.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1959, American Motors hired designer Dick Teague, who had previously worked for General Motors, Packard, and Chrysler; after Edmund E.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Anderson left the company in 1961, Teague was named principal designer and in 1964, vice president.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] To stay competitive, American Motors produced a wide range of products during the 1960s and added innovations long before the "Big Three" introduced them.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] For example, the Rambler Classic was equipped with a standard tandem master cylinder in 1962 that provided stopping ability even if there was a failure in the brake system.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Only Cadillac also included this safety feature six years before U.S. safety regulations required it on all cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automotive industry, American Motors offered adjustable front seat backrests from their Nash-origin, and in 1964, the Classic and Ambassador were equipped with standard dual reclining front seats nearly a decade before the Big Three offered them as options.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Bendix disc brakes were made standard on the Marlin and optional on other models in 1965.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made the Marlin one of the first modern American cars with standard disc brakes, while the Big Three did not offer them until the early 1970s on most of their models to meet Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the early part of the decade, sales were strong, thanks in no small part to the company's history of building small cars, which came into vogue in 1961.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In both 1960 and 1961, Ramblers ranked in third place among U.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automobile sales, up from third on the strength of small-car sales, even in the face of a lot of new competition.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's strategic focus was very successful, as reflected in the firm's healthy profits year after year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company became completely debt-free.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The financial success allowed the company to reach an agreement on August 26, 1961, with the United Auto Workers for a profit sharing plan that was new in the automobile industry.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its new three-year labor contract included generous annual improvement pay increases, and automatic cost-of-living raises.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, in 1962, Romney resigned to run for Governor of Michigan.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] His replacement was Roy Abernethy, American Motors' successful sales executive.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] By 1964, Studebaker production in the United States had ended, and its Canadian operations ceased in 1966.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "Big Three", plus the smaller American Motors, Kaiser Jeep, International Harvester, Avanti, and Checker companies were the remaining North American auto manufacturers.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy believed that American Motors's reputation of building reliable, economical cars could translate into a new strategy that could follow AMC buyers as they traded into larger, more expensive vehicles.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors, in reality, had produced large cars throughout its history.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler Ambassadors were as large as a full-sized Ford or Chevy.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] There was only an absence of largest-sized cars from the American Motors lineup in 1963 and 1964 The first cars bearing his signature were the 1965 models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1965 models were a major makeover of the new platform that had just been introduced in 1963.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] These were a longer Ambassador series and new convertibles for the larger models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] During mid-year, a fastback, called the Marlin, was added.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] It competed directly with cars like the Dodge Charger, but AMC's "family-sized" fastback emphasized personal-luxury.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The continuing quest "in the business world's toughest race – the grinding contest against the Big Three automobile makers" also meant annual styling changes requiring large expenditures.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors's management total confidence "that the new 1965 models would stem a bothersome decline" actually began falling behind in share of sales.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Moreover, a new line of redesigned cars in the full and mid-sized markets was launched in the fall of 1966.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The cars won acclaim for their fluid styling, and Abernethy's ideas did work as Ambassador sales increased significantly.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, the dated designs of the Rambler Americans hurt its sales, which offset gains from Ambassador sales.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] There were quality control problems with introducing the new full-sized cars and persistent rumors of the company's demise because of its precarious cash flow.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Consumer Reports' negative ratings for American Motors' safety did not help.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] During this time, AMC's international sales were expanding.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] From only 18,000 cars five years ago, the 1965 model year AMC sold 74,420 vehicles in Canada, Europe, and Latin America.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC remained the most significant U.S. seller of autos in both France and Germany.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy also called for the de-emphasis of the Rambler brand because he believed the public associated it too strongly with economy cars and that it was hindering the sale of American Motors' other models at a time when mid and luxury car sales were robust.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, he ordered that for 1966, the Ambassador and Marlin were to be badged purely as a product of American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The strategy shift at first seemed to be working because sales of the redesigned 1965 and 1966 Ambassadors improved, even as AMC's overall production decreased from the record level achieved in 1963.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, corporate earnings per share were a meager 27 cents per share, the lowest since AMC made its famous compact car comeback in 1958.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Investors received a message of the changing fortune of the automaker when the company's 1966 annual financial report was delivered in a plain brown wrapper, instead of the previous year's glossy cover.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] A completely new design was also slated for the larger 1967 models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This strategy added $60 million in retooling costs, a significant stretch for the company.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The latest models shared fewer parts and were more expensive to build.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy continued his objective to position the new Rebel and Ambassador designs on an equal basis with competitive economy models marketed by the Big Three.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors did not have their own electric car program as did the Big Three, and after some negotiation, a contract was drawn in 1967 with Gulton Industries to develop a new battery based on lithium and a speed controller designed by Victor Wouk.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] A nickel-cadmium battery powered 1969 Rambler station wagon demonstrated the power systems that according to the scientist was a "wonderful car".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was also the start of other "plug-in"-type experimental American Motors vehicles developed with Gulton – the Amitron city concept car and later the similar Electron.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the new models were well received by the motor industry media, the last quarter sales for AMC ended September 30, 1966 (AMC was not on a calendar fiscal year) were disappointing.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company recorded a balance sheet loss of $12,648,000 for the year before Tax Credits and deferred Tax Assets.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time the board had lost confidence in Abernethy due to his vast spending which had unstabilized the company and each year under his leadership the company had suffered substantial financial losses.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, Abernethy was forced into taking an "early retirement" from American Motors on January 9, 1967.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin quickly instituted changes to American Motors's offerings and tried to regain market share by focusing on younger demographic markets.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin's first decision was to cut the price of the Rambler to within $200 of the basic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Innovative marketing ideas included making air conditioning standard on all 1968 Ambassador models (available as a delete option).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made American Motors the first U.S. automaker to make air conditioning standard equipment on a line of cars, preceding even luxury makes such as Lincoln, Imperial, and Cadillac.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company introduced exciting entries for the decade's muscle car boom, most notably the AMX.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, the Javelin served as the company's entrant into the sporty pony car market created by the Plymouth Barracuda and the Ford Mustang.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Additional operating cash was derived in 1968 through the sale of Kelvinator Appliance, once one of the firm's core operating units.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Kelvinator divestiture left American Motors a downsized company solely manufacturing automobiles.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler marque was discontinued for the larger 1968 domestic models, leaving only the small Rambler American as the last product to bear the name through 1969.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler brand continued to be used only for export markets, with Mexico being the last market to use it in 1983.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, American Motors was the brand used for all American Motors passenger cars, and all vehicles from that date bore the American Motors name and the new corporate logo.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "American Motors" and "AMC" were used interchangeably in corporate literature well into the 1980s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The branding issue was further complicated when the company's Eagle all-wheel drive passenger cars were marketed as the American Eagle in the 1980s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the late 1960s, Kaiser Industries Corporation decided to leave the automotive industry and sought a buyer for its money-losing Kaiser Jeep division.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' vice president for manufacturing, Gerald C.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers, headed the team sent to evaluate Kaiser's Jeep factories.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although opposed by AMC's top management, Chapin made a significant decision in February 1970 to purchase Kaiser Jeep for $70 million.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although it was a gamble, Chapin believed Jeep vehicles would complement American Motors' passenger car business.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] (The latter being the only Nissan-branded vehicle in the United States until the 1980s when the Datsun name was phased out in favor of Nissan.) Jeep by far had the largest market share of the 4x4 market during this time.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors gained the iconic Jeep brand of light trucks and SUVs, as well as Kaiser-Jeep's government contracts – notably the M151 line of military Jeeps and the DJ-Series postal Jeeps.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also expanded its international network.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The military and special products business was reconstituted as "American Motors General Products Division", later reorganized as AM General.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1970, American Motors consolidated all passenger cars under one distinct brand identity and debuted the Hornet range of compact cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet and the later Gremlin shared platforms.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Gremlin, the first North American-built subcompact, sold more than 670,000 units from 1970 through 1978.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet became American Motors' best-selling passenger car since the Rambler Classic, with more than 860,000 units sold when production ended in 1977.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet platform continued to be built under various models through 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] For a time, both the Hornet and Gremlin could be ordered with Levi's denim interiors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors supplied Mark VII Limited owner Jack Webb with two Matadors, a sedan and a wagon, for use in his popular television series *Adam-12*, increasing the cars' public profile.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matadors saw fleet use as taxis, government, police, and fire vehicles in some states.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1973, American Motors signed a licensing agreement with Curtiss-Wright to build Wankel engines for cars and Jeeps.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting in 1974, the Matador sedan and station wagon were mildly refreshed, with new boxier front and rear ends, making it full-sized.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This second-generation model was produced virtually unchanged until 1978.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sagging sales and tight finances resulted in the discontinuation of the Matador line after the 1978 model leaving American Motors to focus almost exclusively on its Hornet platform-based cars and the Jeep line.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, the Rebel and Ambassador were identical from the A-pillar back.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador continued as AMC's upmarket model with higher trim, more equipment, and air conditioning as standard.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] From the A-pillar forward, the Ambassador was redesigned and stretched 7 inches (178 mm) to become the biggest ever, just as the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo sparked gasoline rationing across the nation.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The additional length was due to a new front-end design and more substantial energy-absorbing bumpers required of all automobiles sold in the U.S.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of all large cars fell due to economic problems and rising gasoline prices.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador became a full-sized car in 1974 and was discontinued after the 1974 model year, leaving only the Matador as American Motors' full-size offering.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nash and American Motors made Ambassadors from 1927 through 1974, the longest use of the same model name for any American Motors product and, at the time, the longest continuously used nameplate in the industry.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, the first-generation Matador two-door hardtop, known as the "flying brick" due to its poor aerodynamics in NASCAR competition, was replaced with a sleek, smoothly shaped, and radically styled two-door coupe.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The model received praise for its design, including "Best Styled Car of 1974" by *Car and Driver* magazine, customer satisfaction, and sold almost 100,000 coupes over five years.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador Coupe shared few components with the Matador sedan and station wagon other than suspension, drive train, some trim, and interior parts.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, American Motors's AM General subsidiary began building urban transit buses in cooperation with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] A total of 5,431 *Metropolitan* buses, including 219 electric trolley buses, were built before production ceased in 1979.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of diesel buses had ceased in 1978, with only trolley bus production taking place in 1979.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer, an innovative all-new model introduced in March 1975 and marketed as "the first wide small car", was a subcompact designed to provide the comfort of a full-sized car.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its pre-production development coincided with tightened U.S. federal passenger emissions and auto safety regulations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer sold well its first two years with 262,772 combined units sold in the US.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] With the Arab Oil Embargo of 1973, General Motors aborted the Wankel rotary engine around which the Pacer had been designed, as its fuel consumption exceeded that of conventional engines with similar power.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Therefore, American Motors's existing 258 and 232 cu in (4.2 and 3.8 L) AMC Straight-6 engines were used in the Pacer instead.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fuel economy was better than the expected rotary engine's, but the I6's gas mileage was relatively low in light of the new focus on energy efficiency.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Also, as the Pacer shared few components other than the drivetrain with other American Motors cars, it was expensive to make, and the cost increased when sales fell steeply after the first two years.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer line was discontinued in mid-1980.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "AMC used cars, as far back as 1967, had the advantage of good warranty coverage ... so most owners were conscious of low-cost car maintenance ...
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC units became some of the very best buys on the used car market" by 1975.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1977 Gremlin had redesigned headlights, grille, rear hatch, and fascia.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] For economy in the fuel crisis, American Motors offered the car with a more fuel-efficient Volkswagen-designed Audi 4-cylinder engine 2.0 L (122 cu in).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The engine was expensive for American Motors to build, and the Gremlin retained the less costly but less economical 232 cu in (3.8 L) as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was a sporty appearance package on the Hornet hatchback featuring upgrades, as well as the 258 cu in (4.2 L) inline six as standard with a choice of three-speed automatic or four-speed manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was optional with the automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] As all Matadors now received standard equipment that was formerly optional (e.g., power steering, automatic transmission), the "Brougham" package was dropped from 1977.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Optional on the Matador coupe was a landau vinyl roof with opera windows, and top-line Barcelonas offered new two-tone paint.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1978 model year, the Hornet platform was redesigned with an adaptation of the new Gremlin front-end design and renamed AMC Concord.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors targeted it at the emerging "premium compact" market segment, paying particular attention to ride and handling, standard equipment, trim, and interior luxury.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gremlins borrowed the Concord instrument panel, a Hornet AMX-inspired GT sports appearance package, and a new striping treatment for X models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer hood was modified to clear a V8 engine, and a Sports package replaced the former X package.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] With falling sales of Matador Coupes, sedans, and wagons, their 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was dropped, leaving only the 258 cu in (4.2 L) Inline-6 (standard on coupes and sedans) and the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 (optional on coupes and sedans, standard on wagons).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The two-tone Barcelona luxury package was offered on Matador sedans, and two-tone red paint was introduced as an additional Barcelona option.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matador production ceased at the end of the model year with total sales of 10,576 units.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador was no longer attractive as automakers struggled to overcome economic woes, including continuing fuel price increases and double-digit U.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1979 model year, the Spirit sedan replaced the Gremlin.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] A new fastback version of the car, the Spirit Liftback, proved successful.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December, Pacer production ceased after a small run of 1980 models was built to use up parts stock.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concords received a new front-end treatment, and in their final season, hatchbacks became available in DL trim.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concord and Spirit models were dropped after 1983.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, Time noted record Jeep sales and a backlog of orders for AM General's buses.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1977, it was announced that the General Services Administration of the Federal U.S. government had awarded AMC a three-year contract worth $15 million to lease 5,838 cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Since the beginning of the fiscal year on October 1, 1976, the GSA had purchased 8,700 cars from AMC for $30 million.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] On October 21, 1977, Roy Chapin Jr. retired, and Gerald C.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] On March 31, 1978, American Motors and Renault announced a sweeping agreement for jointly manufacturing and distributing cars and trucks that would benefit both.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] A month later, American Motors announced that it would halt the production of standard urban transit buses after about 4,300 were sold by its AM General subsidiary over a period of three years.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Environmental Protection Agency ordered the recall of all American Motors's 1976 cars (except those conforming to California emissions regulations) – some 270,000 vehicles— plus 40,000 1975 and 1976 Jeeps and mini trucks, for correction of a fault in the pollution control system.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Total cost was estimated at up to $3 million, or more than AMC had earned the previous quarter.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors lost an estimated $65 million on its conventional (non-Jeep) cars for the fiscal year that ended September 30, 1978, but strong Jeep sales helped the company to an overall $36.7 million profit on sales of $2.6 billion.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, American Motors faced costly engineering work to bring their Jeeps into compliance with a federal directive for all 4-wheel-drive vehicles to average 15 mpg‑US (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) by 1981.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December 1978 the government of Iran, embroiled in the Iranian revolution, cut off oil exports to the world.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This caused a devastating effect on all American automobile makers and American consumers.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gasoline prices jumped 52 percent between September and December 1979.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Each of the Big Three (Ford, General Motors, Chrysler) lost money throughout 1979 leading to Chrysler becoming insolvent and considering bankruptcy by September.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ford survived only because of its European operations, eventually losing $7 billion in domestic sales from 1979 to 1982.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] During the crisis, and with its domestic market share at 1.83%, American Motors struck a deal with Renault, the nationally owned French automaker in October 1979.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC would receive a $150 million cash injection, $50 million in credits, and also the rights to start building the Renault 5 in 1982 (a deal for Renault products to be sold through the American Motors-Jeep dealer network had already been made in 1979).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In return, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was not the first time the two companies had worked together.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking a prestige model line in the early 1960s, Renault assembled CKD kits and marketed Rambler cars in France.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] A drop in Jeep sales caused by the declining economy and soaring energy prices began to constrict American Motors' cash flow.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, pressure increased on the company's non-Jeep product lines.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The face-lifts and rebranding of American Motors' once-innovative and successful cars were not enough in a competitive landscape that had changed dramatically.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] No longer was the threat limited to the Big Three automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response to the 1979 oil crisis, the Big Three had resorted to importing foreign motor vehicles, mainly Japanese models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Japanese models were mass-marketed and had lower manufacturing costs.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] By the end of 1980 Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Indeed, the share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Japanese manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, and Nissan) used streamlined production methods such as outsourcing and Just In Time (JIT) supply-chain management.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] They had new, highly efficient assembly plants in the United States.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] And now they targeted the heart of American Motors' passenger product line: small cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In early 1980, the banks refused American Motors further credit.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking both capital and resources for the new, truly modern products it needed to offer, the company turned to Renault for a $90 million loan (US$351,676,090 in 2025 dollars).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] By September that year, American Motors's U.S. market share had fallen to 1.7%, and in November sales dropped 19.1%.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors warned stockholders that the company could be bankrupted if they did not approve a plan for Renault to acquire as much as 59% of the company.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] On December 16, 1980, American Motors shareholders "overwhelmingly approved making the French Government-owned Renault" their company's principal owner.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Jean-Marc Lepeu, former corporate treasurer at Renault, became vice president for finance at American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In September 1981, Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault veteran of 23 years, mainly in manufacturing, became American Motors' executive vice president for manufacturing.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1982, the company's president W.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers as chairman and CEO, and Dedeurwaerder moved up to be president.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time Renault owned 46% of American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dedeurwaerder brought a broad perspective at this critical time: he is credited with streamlining many of American Motors' arcane management techniques.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] He also instituted important improvements in plant layouts, as well as in cost and quality control.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Having increased its stake in the company several times to keep it solvent, Renault eventually owned 49% in 1983.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Some view this development as ending American Motors' run as a truly American car company.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] New ownership and management heralded a new product venture for American Motors: a line of modern front-wheel drive cars, designed by Renault, to be produced at Kenosha.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1980, all American Motors cars received a new rust-proofing process using Ziebart as Factory Rust Protection.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The extra protection also included aluminized trim screws, plastic inner fender liners, and galvanized steel in every exterior body panel, along with the unibody getting a deep-dip (up to the window line) bath in epoxy-based primer.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In August 1979, for the 1980 model year, American Motors introduced four-wheel-drive versions of the Spirit and Concord, calling the collective line the AMC Eagle.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles rapidly became one of the company's best-known products and are considered one of the first "crossover SUVs".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles used the 2-wheel drive body shells mounted on an all-new platform developed by American Motors in the late 1970s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Featuring an innovative full-time four-wheel-drive system, it sold best in snow-prone areas.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales started strongly but declined over time.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the two-wheel drive Spirit and Concord were discontinued after 1983 as the company concentrated on its new Renault Alliance, the Eagle survived for five years longer, albeit only in station wagon form, into the 1988 model year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This meant the four-wheel-drive Eagle was the lone representative of the American Motors brand from 1984 until the 1988 model year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] All the company's remaining output was branded Renault or Jeep.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The last AMC Eagle was built on December 14, 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Renault Alliance was the first joint product of the American Motors-Renault partnership.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Introduced in 1983, the Alliance was a front-wheel-drive Renault 9 compact car slightly restyled for the American market by Dick Teague, mainly to comply with American safety standards, and produced by American Motors at Kenosha.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The car was badged as a Renault, and some cars also carried American Motors badges.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was available as a sedan with two or four doors and later as a convertible.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The hatchback, introduced in 1984 and badged as the Renault Encore, was the same as the European Renault 11 model.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new model, introduced during increased interest in small cars, won several awards, including Motor Trend Car of the Year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] *Motor Trend* declared: "The Alliance may well be the best-assembled first-year car we've ever seen.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Way to go Renault!" The Alliance was listed as number one on *Car and Driver's* list of ten best cars for 1983.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The positive reception and sales of 200,000 Alliances by 1984 was hindered by the availability of only two body styles.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Alliance was a European-designed car that was not fully suited to U.S. market demands.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The distribution network was also not well supported, which led to the lower quality delivered by dealerships with "disastrous consequences" for the image of the automobiles and high warranty costs because of quality failings, which greatly impacted sales from 1985 to the end of production in 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the 1983 model year, American Motors focused entirely on four-wheel drive autos; the company stopped producing rear-wheel-drive cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors facilities were then used to assemble the Renault-branded Alliance and Encore compact and subcompact cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the final 1987 model year, a higher-performance version of the Alliance 2-door sedan and the convertible was sold as the Renault GTA.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] This version had a Renault two-liter engine that was exclusive to it and not shared with the European Renault 9 and 11 models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Encore models were renamed Alliance Hatchback in 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Alliance and GTA production ended in June of that year, while the Renault 9 and 11 models continued through the 1988 model year in Europe, being replaced by the all-new Renault 19.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] More beneficial to American Motors' future was the introduction of an all-new line of compact Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer models in the autumn of 1983 for the 1984 model year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault's François Castaing, head of AMC's product development team, designed the new Jeep platform with styling by Dick Teague.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault was interested in selling the Cherokee in Europe, but the vehicle needed to be lighter and more fuel-efficient to meet European expectations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new XJ weighed 3,100 pounds (1,406 kilograms), due to its unibody construction and lighter components such as the front seats taken from the Renault 9 and 11 and new Renault Alliance.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC's initial forecasts of 40,000 Cherokee and Wagoneer sales were shattered, with sales amounting to 75,000 in their first year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The three leading off-roading magazines, *Petersen's 4-Wheel & Off-Road*, *Four Wheeler*, and *Off-Road* each named the new Jeep Cherokee as the "4x4 of the year." The popularity of these downsized Jeeps pioneered a new market segment for what later became defined as the sport utility vehicle (SUV).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] They initially used the AMC 150.4 cu in (2.5 L) OHV four-cylinder engine with a carburetor, and a General Motors-built 2.8 L (171 cu in) carbureted V6 was optional.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1986, throttle-body injection replaced the carburetor on the 2.5 L I4 engines.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] A Renault 2.1 L (128 cu in) Turbo-Diesel I4 diesel was also offered.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting with the 1987 models, a new 4.0 L (244 cu in) I6 engine, derived from the older 258 cu in (4.23 L) I6 with a new head design and an electronic fuel injection system, replaced the outsourced V6.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' "new" engine was designed with help from Renault and incorporated Renault-Bendix (Renix) parts for fuel and ignition management.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 4.0 developed an outstanding reputation for reliability and toughness.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Retained by Chrysler after the buyout, the design received continuous improvements and refinements until its discontinuation at the end of the 2006 model year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC 4.0 engine saw extensive application in XJ Cherokees and Wagoneers, Grand Cherokees, and Wranglers, and many of those engines saw (or are seeing) extremely long lives, quite a few exceeding 300,000 mi (480,000 km).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chrysler built the XJ Cherokee until the end of the 2001 model year in the U.S. and until 2005 in China.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Unlike most sport-utility vehicles based on adapted pickup truck designs, the Cherokee XJ SUV came first, and the Comanche was designed as a later pickup truck version.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of the full-sized pickups ceased after 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Grand Wagoneer and 360 V8 engine were dropped after 1991 (the last American-made vehicle whose engine used a carburetor for fuel delivery), and the Comanche was discontinued after 1992.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Significant changes occurred in 1985 as the market moved away from American Motors' small models.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] With fuel relatively cheap again, buyers turned to larger, more powerful automobiles, and American Motors was unprepared for this development.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even the venerable Jeep CJ-5 was dropped after a *60 Minutes* TV news magazine staged exposé of rollover tendencies under extreme conditions.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors also confronted an angry workforce.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Labor was taking revenge, and reports circulated about the sabotage of vehicles on the assembly lines because of the failure to receive promised wage increases.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] There were rumors that the aging Kenosha plant was to be shut down.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the same time, Chrysler was having trouble meeting the demand for its M-body rear-drive models (Dodge Diplomat, Plymouth Gran Fury, and Chrysler Fifth Avenue).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Because they were assembled using the old "gate and buck system" and the tooling could be easily moved, Chrysler could supply the components and control the quality while AMC assembled the car.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy agreed to use some of AMC's idle plant capacity in Kenosha.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1985, Renault's chairman in France, Bernard Hanon, was dismissed by the government in a shake-up triggered by huge losses as a result of his goal to revolutionize Renault's product strategy in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was instrumental in 1981 for the company to invest in AMC and also made Renault a full-line automaker, but this ballooned the firm's debt.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault relinquished its number one sales position in Europe, which it held from 1980 until 1983.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company had been losing money since 1981 and had fallen to sixth place behind Ford, Fiat, Volkswagen, Peugeot, and General Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Strikes plagued Renault at the end of 1984, and the French government introduced price controls that severely cut the profit margins on cars sold in France, Renault's most important market.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Hanon was replaced by Georges Besse, ex-president of Produits Chimiques Ugine Kuhlmann in France.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Paul Tippett resigned to become president of a textile company.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Dedeurwaerder, president since 1982 and chief executive officer since September 1984, announced at the Paris Auto Show in October 1985, that AMC would begin imports of the innovative seven-seat, front-wheel-drive Espace minivan in the spring of 1986.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] This was part of expanding the range of Renault models that include plans for marketing the Renault Alpine GTA/A510 sports car through select AMC dealers.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In December 1985, Dedeurwaerder became chairman of AMC's executive committee while continuing as the company's president and CEO.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Joe Cappy was moved up from executive vice president to chief operating officer, and Tippet's position was filled by an ex-Renault vice president, Pierre Semerena.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Semerena made his managerial reputation as a no-nonsense cost cutter.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The new management responded with tactical moves by selling the lawn care Wheel Horse Products Division and signing an agreement to build Jeeps in the People's Republic of China.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Pentagon had problems with AM General, a significant defense contractor, being managed by a partially French-government-owned firm.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The U.S. government would not allow a foreign government to own a substantial portion of an important defense supplier.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] As a result, the profitable AM General Division was sold to LTV Corporation.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another milestone within AMC's management was the departure of Dick Teague.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was American Motors' design vice president for 23 years - an industry record. he was responsible for many Jeep and AMC designs, including the Javelin, AMX, Hornet, Gremlin, Pacer, Matador coupe, and the Cherokee XJ.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In France, Renault continued to experience financial trouble.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The investment in American Motors (including the construction of a new Canadian assembly plant in Brampton, Ontario) forced cuts at home, resulting in the closure of several French plants and mass layoffs.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, Jeep vehicles were riding an unprecedented surge in demand.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] It seemed to Besse and others that American Motors was on course for profitability.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, on November 17, 1986, Besse, who had a high-profile among French capitalists, was assassinated by a member of a French clandestine far-left extremist group, Action Directe.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] AMC's plans to reinvigorate sales with higher-priced Renaults continued for a little longer, with the plan being a three-pronged lineup beginning with the mid-sized Medallion, the larger Premier above it, and the sporty Renault Alpine providing a halo car.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Medallion and the Premier both went on sale, but Alpine never made its planned mid-1987 rollout.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under pressure from Renault executives following Besse's death, Renault's new president, Raymond Levy, set out to repair employee relations and divest the company of its investment in American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault owned 46.1% of American Motors' outstanding shares of stock.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1986, American Motors posted a $91.3 million loss.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The earlier agreement between Chrysler and American Motors in 1985, under which American Motors would produce M-body chassis rear-drive large cars for five years from mid-1986 through 1990, fed the rumor that Chrysler was about to buy AMC.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to the head of manufacturing for Chrysler, Stephan Sharf, the existing relationship with AMC producing a car for a competitor facilitated the negotiations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 9, 1987, Chrysler agreed to buy Renault's share in American Motors, plus all the remaining shares, for about $1.5 billion ($4,250,878,735 in 2025 dollars).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler made no secret that they were only interested in AMC for Jeep, AMC's new assembly plant in Canada, and AMC's network of 1,300 dealerships nationwide.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] With the sale complete, American Motors became the Jeep-Eagle division of Chrysler on August 25, 1988, and was fully merged as of March 29, 1990.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The sale came at a time when the automotive press was enthusiastic about the proposed 1988 lineup of Renault, Eagle, and Jeep vehicles and reported that the small automaker's financial outlook was improving.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' quarterly results for all of 1987 were positive.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler purchased American Motors when the company appeared to be in an excellent financial position with its new product line.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] It was the Jeep brand that Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted – in particular, the ZJ Gen. of the Grand Cherokee, then under development by Jeep engineers, which ultimately proved highly profitable for Chrysler (the nameplate remains in production today).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the buyout included other attractive deal sweeteners for Chrysler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among them was the world-class, brand-new manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, which offered Iacocca an unprecedented opportunity to increase his company's production capacity at a fire-sale price.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors had designed and built the plant in anticipation of building the Renault 25-based Eagle Premier.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault left the U.S. market entirely as a brand in 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Thus, the Renault Medallion was sold through the new Jeep-Eagle division as an Eagle, not a Renault.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep-Eagle division was formed from the American Motors Jeep Renault dealer network.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep and Eagle vehicles were marketed primarily by former American Motors dealers.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors badge was last used on the Eagle Sports Wagon through the 1988 model year, then eliminated, and the Eagle car brand was phased out by 1998.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company that established American Motors was led by Nash-Kelvinator president George W.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason to reap benefits from the strengths of the two firms to battle the much larger "Big Three" automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The merger was initially intended to be three-way, with Packard being the number three.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason had first discussed the possibility of a merger with Packard president James J.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Nance insisted that if Packard were to join, he would have to be the CEO of the new company.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason fully intended to lead the new company, thus the deal did not go through.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Packard acquired Studebaker two months after Nash acquired Hudson.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason became CEO and president of the new company, and Hudson's president A.E.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Barit retired to become an American Motors board member.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason selected long-time Nash associate and future governor of Michigan, George W.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Roy Abernethy, ex-vice president of sales for Willys, was hired to be vice president of sales.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Following Mason's sudden death on October 8, 1954, Romney took over, reorganizing the company and focusing American Motors' future on a new small car line.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason's death also allowed Romney to put an end to any further discussions for a merger between American Motors and Studebaker-Packard.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] By the end of 1957, the legacy Nash and Hudson brands were completely phased out and replaced with the Rambler and Metropolitan brands.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company struggled initially, but Rambler's sales took off under Romney.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] A Rambler won the 1959 Mobil Economy Run, and by 1960, was the third-most-popular brand of automobile in the United States, behind Ford and Chevrolet.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] George Romney left American Motors in 1962 to run for governor in Michigan and was replaced as CEO by Roy Abernethy.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Abernethy had been with AMC since the 1954 merger and as vice president of sales was responsible for successfully building AMC's sales and distribution network during the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] After two model years (1963 and 1964) of only producing compact cars, Abernethy shifted the focus of American Motors back to bigger and more profitable cars such as the Ambassador line and tried to move away from the perceived negative of the Rambler's economy car image.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the enormous costs of developing the new cars and engines meant American Motors now had problems in securing working capital to keep the company going.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors sales dropped 20% in the first half of 1966, and the firm reported a fiscal six-month loss of $4.2 million on sales of $479 million.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Evans invested more than $2 million because American Motors's stock was selling for only 60% of the company's net worth; thus, he became its largest stockholder and was named its chairman on June 6, 1966, replacing Richard E.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cross, who continued as a director and chairman of the executive committee.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the quarter ending September 30, 1966, American Motors recorded a loss of $12,648,000 before tax credits and deferred tax assets.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the face of deteriorating financial and market positions, Abernethy "retired" as CEO in 1967, and Evans "resigned" as chairman.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., the son of Hudson co-founder Roy D.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' public explanation for the removals was that the two had "stepped aside according to a plan to give a younger team an opportunity to move the company forward".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin took charge of revitalizing the company, and designer Dick Teague economized by developing several vehicles from common stampings.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The AMC Matador was in reality a facelift of the AMC Rebel, itself derived from the 1967 AMC Ambassador platform.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] While prices and costs were cut, Teague designed new and more sporty automobiles resulting in the Javelin and AMX muscle cars; and the AMC Hornet.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] From 1970 Jeep production complemented AMC's existing passenger-car business.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Chapin's leadership, AMC produced all-new compact car designs based on the Hornet platform including the Gremlin and Concord.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers replaced the retiring William Luneburg as president and Chief Operating Officer.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Only 5 months later, upon the retirement of Chapin, Meyers became chairman and CEO on October 21, 1977.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Meyers was 49 years old, and became the youngest top executive in the automobile industry.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers abandoned AMC's policy of head-on competition and instead focused on revamping its four-wheel drive vehicles, a market segment left untended by the large automakers, and by acquiring advanced technology.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyer's began talks with Renault in 1979 and from 1980, American Motors partnered with the French automaker to help finance their manufacturing operations, obtain much-needed capital, and source subcompact vehicles.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] On December 16, 1980, Renault became the principal owner of American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] At age 53, Meyers retired from the company in February 1982.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] By that time, Renault controlled 46% of American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers was succeeded as chairman by former American Motors president W.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Tippett was a member of American Motors management for only three years but had overseen almost all vehicle-making operations during his time as president.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault manager, replaced Tippet as president.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Tippet's tenure as CEO was short-lived and in September 1984, he was replaced by Dedeurwaerder.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] On September 28, 1984, Dedeurwaerder was promoted to CEO, with Tippett remaining on as chairman.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] On February 25, 1985, AMC announced its first full-year profit since 1979.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The success was short-lived as on July 31, 1985, AMC announced that it had received a $50 million loan from Renault following a second-quarter loss of $70.4 million.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Dedeurwaerder, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors in 1985 to produce Dodge Diplomats and Plymouth Furys, as well as Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in American Motors' Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, American Motors had excess manufacturing capacity.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1986, Dedeurwaerder was named Renault's executive vice president of worldwide sales and marketing.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] He remained president and CEO, and chairman of the executive committee at AMC until March 23, 1986, when he was succeeded in the former two roles by Joseph E.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] By 1986, Renault had lost $700 million on $22 billion of sales in the U.S. market, and was $9 billion in debt.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 23, 1986, former executive vice president of operations Joseph E.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy was named president and chief executive officer of American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler acquired American Motors in August 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The primary task of Chrysler management was to integrate the two companies as quickly as possible.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' final CEO, was tasked with achieving this by Chrysler president Gerald Greenwald.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] After the buyout Cappy joined Chrysler as group vice president of the new Jeep-Eagle division.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1989, he was named Chrysler's vice president of brand development.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The following year he became Chrysler's vice president of international operations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was forced to constantly innovate for 33 years until Chrysler absorbed it in 1987.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The lessons learned from this experience were integrated into the company that bought American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The organization, strategies, and several key executives allowed Chrysler to gain an edge over the competition.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even today, the lessons gained from the American Motors experience continue to benefit other firms in the industry.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] There are many legacies of American Motors's business strategies.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors could formulate strategies that industry critics often evaluated as "strokes of brilliance".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., American Motors realized they were up against the giants of the industry, so to compete successfully they had to be able to move quickly and with ingenuity.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] An essential strategy practiced by American Motors was to rely on outside vendors to supply components in which they had differential advantages.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] This approach was finally accepted within the U.S. auto industry, but only after each of the Big Three experienced the failure of attempting to be self-sufficient.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another example of American Motors' agility was the ability of management to squeeze money out of reluctant bankers, even in the face of bankruptcy.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] These core abilities helped save the company from collapse and, after each obstacle, gave it the wherewithal to keep it operating.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Ironically, American Motors was never stronger than just before its demise.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' managers anticipated important trends in the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] It preached fuel efficiency in the 1950s, long before most auto buyers demanded it.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Led by American Motors' Rambler and several European cars, the small car innovation reduced the Big Three's market share from 93% in 1957 to 82% in 1959.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company inherited foreign manufacturing and sales partnerships from Nash and continued developing business relations, decades before most of the international consolidations among automobile makers took place.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was the first U.S. automaker to establish an ownership agreement with a foreign automaker, Renault.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although small in size, American Motors was able to introduce numerous industry innovations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Starting in 1957, American Motors was the only U.S. manufacturer to fully immerse all automobile bodies in primer paint for protection against rust, until competitors adopted the practice in 1964.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even one of American Motors's most expensive new product investments (the Pacer) established many features that were later adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] These included aerodynamic body design, space-efficient interiors, aircraft-style doors, and a large greenhouse for visibility.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was also effective in other areas, such as marketing, by introducing low-rate financing.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' four-wheel-drive vehicles established the foundation for the modern SUV market segments, and "classic" Jeep models remain the benchmark in this field.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin drew on his experiences as a hunter and fisherman and marketed the Jeep brand successfully to people with like interests.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The brand developed a cult appeal that continues.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase of American Motors was instrumental in reviving Chrysler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Robert Lutz, former president of Chrysler, the American Motors acquisition was a big and risky undertaking.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase was part of Chrysler's strategic "retreat-cum-diversification" plan that he states did not have the proper focus.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Initially, the goal was to obtain the world-renowned Jeep brand.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, Lutz discovered that the decision to buy American Motors turned out to be a gold mine for Chrysler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] At that time, Chrysler's management was attempting to find a model to improve structure and operations, *"something that would help get our minds unstuck and thinking beyond the old paradigms that we were so familiar with*".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this transformation, *"Chrysler's acquisition of AMC was one of the all-time great moments in corporate serendipity*" according to Lutz *" that most definitely played a key role in demonstrating how to accomplish change*".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Lutz (1993), while American Motors had its share of problems, it was far from being a bunch of "brain-dead losers".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] He describes the "troops" at American Motors as more like the Wake Island Marines in battle, "with almost no resources, and fighting a vastly superior enemy, they were able to roll out an impressive succession of new products".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] After first reacting with anger to the purchase, Chrysler managers soon anticipated the benefits.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] To further solidify the organizational competencies held by American Motors, Lee Iacocca agreed to retain former American Motors units, such as engineering, completely intact.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, American Motors' lead engineer, François Castaing, was made head of all engineering at Chrysler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In an unthinkable strategic move, Castaing completely dismantled the entrenched Chrysler groups.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In their place, American Motors's "platform team" was implemented.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] These were close-knit cross-functional groups responsible for the whole vehicle, contrasted with Chrysler's highly functional structure.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this capacity, Castaing's strategy was to eliminate the corporate administrative overhead bureaucracy.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] This move shifted corporate culture and agitated veteran executives who believed that Chrysler's reputation as "the engineering company" was being destroyed.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Yet, according to the popular press, by the 1980s, Chrysler's reputation was shot, and in Lutz's view, only dramatic action would change that.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In summary, Chrysler's purchase of American Motors laid the critical foundation to help re-establish a strategy for its revival in the 1990s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Top managers at Chrysler after the AMC buyout appeared to have made errors similar to those by American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] For example, Chrysler invested heavily in new untested models while not keeping up its profitable high-volume lines.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors influence also continued at General Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM recruited a new executive team to turn itself from near bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among the new strategists at GM was Lutz, who understood the importance of passion in product design.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Lutz's new thinking at GM incorporated the systems and structures that originated from American Motors's lean and focused operations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault implemented the lessons it learned from its investment in American Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The French firm took a parallel approach as it did with its initial ownership of American Motors and applied it to resurrect the money-losing Nissan automaker in Japan.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 2009, in a deal brokered by the Obama administration, Italian automaker Fiat initiated a white knight takeover of Chrysler to save the struggling automaker from liquidation.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The two firms would later fully merge to create Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, and would further merge with the French firm PSA Group, owners of the Citroën and Peugeot brands, to form Stellantis in 2021.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler revived the "Spirit" name, which was discontinued by AMC after 1983 for use on one of its A platform cars (the Dodge Spirit) from 1989 until 1995.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The planned Renault Medallion was sold as the Eagle Medallion in 1988 and 1989.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The full-sized Premier's platform was far more advanced than anything Chrysler was building.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Plymouth almost received their rendition of the LH platform, which was to be called the Accolade.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Still, Chrysler decided to drop this version just before LH production started.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Chrysler 300M was likewise a Premier/LH-derived car and was initially to have been the next-generation Eagle Vision until the Eagle brand was dropped after 1998.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The LH Platform was subsequently re-engineered, using Mercedes-Benz components, into the Chrysler LX Platform, which was the basis for the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger, and Dodge Challenger.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler's successor Stellantis later revived the Hornet name in 2023 for Dodge as a rebadged variant of the Alfa Romeo Tonale.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler marketed the SJ Jeep Grand Wagoneer until 1991, leaving it almost entirely unaltered from the final American Motors rendition before the buyout.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep Comanche pickup truck remained until 1992, while the Cherokee remained until 2001 in the United States.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The XJ Cherokee was produced in China through 2006 as the Cherokee 2500 (2.5L) and Cherokee 4000 (4.0L).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although it was not introduced until 1993, the Jeep Grand Cherokee was initially an American Motors-developed vehicle.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Traces of American Motors remained within.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' Toledo, Ohio, plants continued to manufacture the Jeep Wrangler and Liberty, as well as parts and components for Chrysler, Dodge, and Jeep vehicles (although Toledo Machining and Forge were closed in 2005).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although heavily downsized, American Motors' main plant in Wisconsin operated as the Kenosha Engine Plant, producing engines for several Chrysler Group products, including the Wrangler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The plant was closed as part of the post-bailout restructuring of Chrysler in October 2010.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 4.0 L (242 cu in) engine was used until the 2006 model year by DaimlerChrysler in the Jeep Wrangler.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' technologically advanced Bramalea Assembly and Stamping Plants in Brampton, Ontario, later produced the LX-cars – the Chrysler 300, Dodge Challenger, Dodge Charger, and the now discontinued Dodge Magnum.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Both were retired when the Wrangler was completely redesigned for the 2007 model year.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General, sold by American Motors in 1983, is still in business building the American Motors-designed Humvee for American and allied militaries.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General also built the now-discontinued civilian variant, the H1, and manufactured a Chevrolet Tahoe-derived companion, the H2, under contract to GM, who acquired the rights to the civilian Hummer brand in 1999.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM was forced to phase out the Hummer brand in early 2010 due to its bankruptcy restructuring after offering it for sale, but failing to find a suitable buyer.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although Chrysler introduced new logos for its brands in the 1990s and again in 2010 after the Fiat Group took control of the company, Jeep still uses the American Motors-era logo introduced shortly after American Motors purchased the brand in 1970.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Until the Chrysler purchase, Jeep's logo also featured the American Motors emblem.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Beginning in 1960, American Motors' executive vice president of international operations Roy D.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr. embarked on a strong international campaign to set up importation and local assembly operations of American Motors vehicles worldwide.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] In five years, Chapin increased foreign sales to 73,489 cars, which at the same time grew AMC's share of the U.S. export market from 2.5 percent to 14.3 percent.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin successfully established or re-established vehicle assembly operations in Argentina, Australia, Belgium (via Renault of France), Chile, Costa Rica, Germany, Iran, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Philippines, South Africa, and Venezuela.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] He also strengthened international export operations with exports to the United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, and Norway in Europe, and to countries in the Middle East, the Caribbean, and South America.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Rambler Classic would become the basis of Argentina's future national car, the Torino.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] After becoming CEO in 1967, Chapin organized the acquisition of Kaiser Jeep from Kaiser Industries in 1970, with American Motors, thereby inheriting all existing international Jeep operations.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] These helped sustain American Motors during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p02] While the Rambler marque had been dropped in the United States after the 1969 model year, all export markets retained the Rambler name, with the longest to retain it being Mexico until 1983.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The initial building was built during 1926–27 by the Electric Refrigeration Corporation (subsequently Nash-Kelvinator) with design by Amedeo Leoni, industrial layout by Wallace McKenzie, and tower enclosure and industrial units by William E.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] War Department contracted with Nash-Kelvinator to produce 900 Sikorsky R-6 model helicopters.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] As part of that contract, a 4.5 acres (1.8 ha) site north of the factory was used as the smallest airport in the world as a flight testing base.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Nash-Kelvinator produced about 50 R-6s a month during the war.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] When the contract was terminated at the war's end, 262 helicopters had been constructed.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] During Chrysler's occupancy of the complex, it was known as Jeep and (Dodge) Truck Engineering (JTE), including facilities for body-on-frame work as well as testing facilities and labs.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The buildings included 1,500,000 square feet (140,000 m2), approximately one-third devoted to engineering and computer functions.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] As of 2007, Chrysler employed over 1,600 people at the complex, moving those operations in mid-2009 to the Chrysler Technology Center.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The property was put up for sale by Chrysler in early 2010.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was bought by a local man who gutted the building for scrap and left it in a dilapidated state before losing it to foreclosure.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The abandoned building was in possession of the city of Detroit and officials were considering if the industrial site would be more marketable if the building was torn down.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 2018, the Wayne County Commission approved a land swap that included a new jail complex for the county as well as a potential revival for the old American Motors building.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The era of 1900 until 1925 saw various corporations, in several U.S. states, use similar "American" names, such as American Motor Carriage Company (Ohio, 1902–1903), American Automobile Manufacturing Company (Indiana, 1911–1912), and American Motors Incorporated (New York, 1919–1920).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1916, an earlier "American Motors Corporation", apparently unrelated to the more famous later corporation of the same name, was formed in Newark, New Jersey, with Louis Chevrolet as vice president and chief engineer.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] By 1918, it was producing cars in a plant at Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1923, it merged with the Bessemer Motor Truck Company of Pennsylvania into Bessemer–American Motors Corporation, which lasted less than a year before merging with the Winther and Northway companies into Amalgamated Motors.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] A new company was formed in Palmdale, California, in 2001.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Registration for the American Motors trademarks was filed in 2001 by this California-based firm.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The company's website specifically claimed no affiliation to the previous American Motors but used American Motors' history and logos on its website.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The website is now dead, and the company's claims to American Motors' trademarks expired in 2005.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The new Chrysler LLC holds a live registration for the name "American Motors", which was applied for in 2005.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The "AMC" wordmark, complete with "A-mark" graphic logo, as was originally used in 1970 and through the late-1980s, was registered and published for comment by Chrysler as of 2010.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Also: Kaiser Jeeps used the AMC 327, Buick 225 ("Dauntless V6"), Buick 350 ("Dauntless V8"), and Willys 134 I4 ("Hurricane").
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The downsized Jeep XJ Cherokee/Wagoneer used the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6 in 1983–1984.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors contracted with Volkswagen to buy tooling for the Audi 2.0 L OHC I4.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Major parts (block, crankshaft, head assembly) were initially purchased from Audi and shipped to the U.S., where American Motors accomplished final assembly at a plant explicitly purchased for the production of this engine.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Sales never reached numbers to justify taking over total production.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors made several changes to the engine.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] By contractual agreement, they were prevented from using the Volkswagen or Audi names in association with the American Motors assembled version.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors models historically regarded by hobbyists as particularly "collectible" include the Javelin, AMX, and performance specials such as the 1957 Rambler Rebel, 1965–67 Marlin, 1969 Hurst SC/Rambler, 1970 Rebel Machine, and 1971 Hornet SC/360.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] These models enjoyed limited popularity when new, resulting in low production figures.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] In January 2007, the AMC AMX was "really taking off in the muscle car market" according to the editors of *Hemmings Classic Car*, and it had "left its mark among AMC collectors' minds as a great alternative" to higher-priced Hemi-powered muscle cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The early Javelin (1968–70) stands out from the Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler pony cars.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays, automotive historian and author of *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, the "Wow!
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Factor" is an important and measurable pleasure to an owner whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Moreover, the author's collector car, a 1969 Ambassador station wagon, made friends as strangers came to greet and host him as if "long lost kin".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays points out the ready availability of parts for American Motors engines and his experiences in having service done on Ramblers without being charged for the work in exchange for the experience of driving a "sassy Rambler" (a 1966 American convertible) and having pictures taken with it.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Other American Motors models, once somewhat ignored by the hobby, are now considered "future collectibles".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] Examples include the 1959 Ambassador 4-door hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were produced, and the Jeep Scrambler CJ8, a combined pickup truck-Jeep, of which only a few thousand were made.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Gremlin is described as having "a cult-like following" in today's collectible car market.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The Gremlin shares components with some other American Motors models, making its repair and restoration relatively inexpensive compared with other "historic cars".
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Pacer increased in value according to a Pacer owner who is the CEO of a major insurance provider for collector car owners.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] There are active Rambler and American Motors car clubs in the U.S. and elsewhere (examples in External Links).
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] In April 2008, *Hot Rod* magazine released an article claiming that American Motors was in the process of being revived.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] The vehicles in the works were to be the AMX, Matador, Ambassador, Pacer, and Gremlin.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was a popular article, illustrated with drawings of the concept cars entering production and accompanied by plentiful information.
[src:dodge-charger/american-motors-corporation-p03] However, it was later revealed as an April Fools' joke.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:dodge-charger/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Bounded by the Atlantic Ocean on the east, Brazil has a coastline of 7,491 kilometers (4,655 mi), among the longest in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Covering roughly half of South America's land area, it borders all other countries and territories on the continent except Ecuador and Chile.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil encompasses a wide range of tropical and subtropical landscapes, as well as wetlands, savannas, plateaus, and low mountains.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It contains most of the Amazon basin, including the world's largest river system and most extensive virgin tropical forest.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil has diverse wildlife, a variety of ecological systems, and extensive natural resources spanning numerous protected habitats.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It ranks first among 17 megadiverse countries, with its natural heritage being the subject of significant global interest, as environmental degradation (through processes such as deforestation) directly affect global issues such as climate change and biodiversity loss.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil was inhabited by various indigenous peoples prior to the landing of Portuguese explorer Pedro Álvares Cabral in 1500.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The territory was subsequently claimed and settled by Portugal, which founded the country's first city, São Vicente, in 1532 and imported enslaved Africans to work on plantations.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil remained a colony until 1815, when it was elevated to a united kingdom with Portugal after the transfer of the Portuguese court to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Prince Pedro of Braganza declared Brazilian independence in 1822 and, after waging a war against Portugal, established the Empire of Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The country's first constitution in 1824 established a bicameral legislature and enshrined principles such as freedom of religion and the press; slavery was gradually abolished until its final abolition in 1888.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil became a presidential republic following a military coup d'état in 1889.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] An armed revolution in 1930 ended the First Republic and brought Getúlio Vargas to power.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Vargas' self-coup in 1937 ushered the authoritarian Estado Novo, in which he oversaw Brazil's involvement in World War II.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Democracy was restored after Vargas' ousting in 1945.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] An authoritarian military dictatorship emerged in 1964 with support from the United States and ruled until 1985, after which civilian governance resumed.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's current constitution, enacted in 1988, defines it as a democratic federal republic.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil is a regional and middle power, and has been described as a rising global power.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It is an emerging, upper-middle income economy and newly industrialized country, with one of the 10 largest economies in the world in both nominal and PPP terms, the largest economy in Latin America and the Southern Hemisphere, and the largest share of wealth in South America.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] With a complex and highly diversified economy, Brazil is one of the world's major or primary exporters of various agricultural goods, mineral resources, and manufactured products.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The country ranks thirteenth in the world by number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil is a founding member of the United Nations, the G20, BRICS, G4, Mercosur, Organization of American States, Organization of Ibero-American States, and the Community of Portuguese Language Countries; it is also an observer state of the Arab League and a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The word *Brazil* probably comes from the Portuguese word for brazilwood, a tree that once grew plentifully along the Brazilian coast.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In Portuguese, brazilwood is called *pau-brasil*, with the word *brasil* commonly given the etymology 'red like an ember', formed from *brasa* ('ember') and the suffix *-il* (from *-iculum* or *-ilium*).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It has alternatively been suggested that this is a folk etymology for a word for the plant related to an Arabic or Asian word for a red plant.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] As brazilwood produces a deep red dye, it was highly valued by the European textile industry and was the earliest commercially exploited product from Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Throughout the 16th century, massive amounts of brazilwood were harvested by indigenous peoples (mostly Tupi) along the Brazilian coast, who sold the timber to European traders in return for assorted European consumer goods.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The official Portuguese name of the land, in original Portuguese records, was the 'Land of the Holy Cross' (*Terra da Santa Cruz*), but European sailors and merchants commonly called it the 'Land of Brazil' (*Terra do Brasil*) because of the brazilwood trade.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Popular usage eclipsed and eventually supplanted the official Portuguese name.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Some early sailors called it the 'Land of Parrots'.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the Guarani language, Brazil is called *Pindorama*, meaning 'land of the palm trees'.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Some of the earliest human remains found in the Americas, Luzia Woman, were found in the area of Pedro Leopoldo, Minas Gerais, and provide evidence of human habitation going back at least 11,000 years.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The earliest pottery ever found in the Western Hemisphere was excavated in the Amazon basin of Brazil and radiocarbon dated to over 8,000 years ago (6000 BC).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The pottery was found near Santarém and provides evidence that the region supported a complex prehistoric culture.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Marajoara culture flourished on Marajó in the Amazon delta from AD 400 to 1400, developing sophisticated pottery, social stratification, large populations, mound building, and complex social formations such as chiefdoms.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Around the time of the Portuguese arrival, the territory of present day Brazil had an estimated Indigenous population of 7 million people, mostly semi-nomadic, who subsisted on hunting, fishing, gathering, and migrant agriculture.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The population comprised several large Indigenous ethnic groups (e.g., the Tupis, Guaranis, and Gês.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Tupi people were subdivided into the Tupiniquins and Tupinambás.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Before the arrival of the Europeans, the boundaries between these groups and their subgroups were marked by wars that arose from differences in culture, language and moral beliefs.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] These wars also involved large-scale military actions on land and water, with cannibalistic rituals on prisoners of war.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] While heredity had some weight, leadership was a status more won over time than assigned in succession ceremonies and conventions.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Slavery among the Indigenous groups had a different meaning than it had for Europeans, since it originated from a diverse socioeconomic organization, in which asymmetries were translated into kinship relations.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Following the 1494 Treaty of Tordesillas, the land now called Brazil was claimed for the Portuguese Empire on 22 April 1500, with the arrival of the Portuguese fleet commanded by Pedro Álvares Cabral.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Along the coast, the Portuguese encountered various Indigenous communities, most of whom spoke languages of the Tupi–Guarani family.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Though the first settlement, São Vicente, was founded in 1532, colonization effectively began in 1534, when King John III of Portugal divided the territory into the fifteen private and autonomous captaincies.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] However, the decentralized and unorganized captaincy system proved unsuccessful, and in 1549 the Portuguese king restructured them into the Governorate General of Brazil in the city of Salvador, which became the capital of a single and centralized Portuguese colony in South America.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the first two centuries of colonization, Indigenous and European groups lived in constant war, establishing opportunistic alliances in order to gain advantages against each other.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil received more than 2.8 million slaves from Africa between the years 1500 and 1800.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] This increased level of immigration in turn caused some conflicts between newcomers and old settlers.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Portuguese expeditions known as *bandeiras* gradually expanded Brazil's original colonial frontiers in South America to its approximately current borders.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In this era, other European powers tried to colonize parts of Brazil, in incursions that the Portuguese had to fight, notably the French in Rio during the 1560s, in Maranhão during the 1610s, and the Dutch in Bahia and Pernambuco, during the Dutch–Portuguese War, after the end of Iberian Union.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In late 1807, Spanish and Napoleonic forces threatened the security of continental Portugal, causing Prince Regent John, in the name of Queen Maria I, to move the royal court from Lisbon to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] There they established some of Brazil's first financial institutions, such as its local stock exchanges and its National Bank, additionally ending the Portuguese monopoly on Brazilian trade and opening Brazil's ports to other nations.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 1809, in retaliation for being forced into exile, the Prince Regent ordered the conquest of French Guiana.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] With the end of the Peninsular War in 1814, the courts of Europe demanded that Queen Maria I and Prince Regent John return to Portugal, deeming it unfit for the head of an ancient European monarchy to reside in a colony.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 1815, to justify continuing to live in Brazil, where the royal court had thrived for six years, the Crown established the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves, thus creating a pluricontinental transatlantic monarchic state.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] However, the leadership in Portugal, resentful of the new status of its larger colony, continued to demand the return of the court to Lisbon (see Liberal Revolution of 1820).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 1821, acceding to the demands of revolutionaries who had taken the city of Porto, John VI departed for Lisbon.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] There he swore an oath to the new constitution, leaving his son, Prince Pedro de Alcântara, as Regent of the Kingdom of Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Tensions between Portuguese and Brazilians increased and the Portuguese Cortes, guided by the new political regime imposed by the Liberal Revolution, tried to re-establish Brazil as a colony.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Brazilians refused to yield, and Prince Pedro decided to side with them, declaring the country's independence from Portugal on 7 September 1822.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] A month later, Prince Pedro was proclaimed the first Emperor of Brazil, with the royal title of Dom Pedro I, resulting in the founding of the Empire of Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Brazilian War of Independence, which had already begun along this process, spread through the northern, northeastern regions and in the Cisplatina province.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The last Portuguese soldiers surrendered on 8 March 1824; Portugal officially recognized Brazilian independence on 29 August 1825.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] As the new Emperor could not exert his constitutional powers until he came of age, a regency was set up by the General Assembly.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] These emerged from the provinces' dissatisfaction with the central power, coupled with old and latent social tensions peculiar to a vast, slaveholding and newly independent nation state.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] This period of internal political and social upheaval, which included the Praieira revolt in Pernambuco, was overcome only at the end of the 1840s, years after the end of the regency, which occurred with the premature coronation of Pedro II in 1841.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] During the last phase of the monarchy, internal political debate centered on the issue of slavery.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The foreign-affairs policies of the monarchy dealt with issues pertaining Brazil's neighboring countries in the Southern Cone.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Long after the Cisplatine War that resulted in the independence of Uruguay, Brazil won three international wars during the 58-year reign of Pedro II: the Platine War, the Uruguayan War and the devastating Paraguayan War, the largest war effort in Brazilian history.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Although there was no desire among the majority of Brazilians to change the country's form of government, on 15 November 1889, in disagreement with the majority of the Imperial Army officers, as well as with rural and financial elites, the monarchy was overthrown by a military coup.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] A few days later, the national flag was replaced with a new design that included the national motto "*Ordem e Progresso*", influenced by positivism.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] 15 November is now Republic Day, a national holiday.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The early republican government was a military dictatorship, with the army dominating affairs both in Rio de Janeiro and in the states.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Freedom of the press disappeared and elections were controlled by those in power.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Not until 1894, following an economic crisis and a military one, did civilians take power, remaining there until October 1930.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Vargas and the military were supposed to assume power temporarily, but instead closed down Congress, extinguished the Constitution, ruled with emergency powers and replaced the states' governors with his own supporters.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the 1930s, three attempts to remove Vargas and his supporters from power failed.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The first was the Constitutionalist Revolution in 1932, led by São Paulo's oligarchy.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The second was a communist uprising in November 1935, and the third a *putsch* attempt by local fascists in May 1938.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The 1935 uprising created a security crisis in which Congress transferred more power to the executive branch.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The 1937 *coup d'état* resulted in the cancellation of the 1938 election and formalized Vargas as dictator, beginning the Estado Novo era.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] During this period, government brutality and censorship of the press increased.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] During World War II, Brazil remained neutral until August 1942, when the country suffered retaliation by Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy in a strategic dispute over the South Atlantic, and, therefore, entered the war on the allied side.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In addition to its participation in the battle of the Atlantic, Brazil also sent an expeditionary force to fight in the Italian campaign.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] With the Allied victory in 1945 and the end of the fascist regimes in Europe, Vargas' position became untenable, and he was swiftly overthrown in another military coup, with democracy reinstated by the same army that had ended it 15 years earlier.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Vargas committed suicide in August 1954 amid a political crisis, after having returned to power by election in 1950.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Several brief interim governments followed Vargas' suicide.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Juscelino Kubitschek became president in 1956 and assumed a conciliatory stance towards the political opposition that allowed him to govern without major crises.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The economy and industrial sector grew remarkably, but his greatest achievement was the construction of the new capital city of Brasília, inaugurated in 1960.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Kubitschek's successor, Jânio Quadros, resigned in 1961 less than a year after taking office.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] His vice-president, João Goulart, assumed the presidency, but aroused strong political opposition and was deposed in April 1964 by a coup that resulted in a military dictatorship.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The new regime was intended to be transitory, but gradually closed in on itself and became a full dictatorship with the promulgation of the Fifth Institutional Act in 1968.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Oppression was not limited to those who resorted to guerrilla tactics to fight the regime, but also reached institutional opponents, artists, journalists and other members of civil society, inside and outside the country through "Operation Condor".
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Like other authoritarian regimes, due to an economic boom, known as the "economic miracle", the Brazilian military dictatorship reached a peak in popularity in the early 1970s.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Slowly, however, the wear and tear of years of dictatorial power had not slowed the repression, even after the defeat of the leftist guerrillas.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The inability to deal with the economic crises of the period and popular pressure made a redemocratization policy inevitable, which from the regime side was led by Generals Ernesto Geisel and Golbery do Couto e Silva.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] With the enactment of the Amnesty Law in 1979, Brazil began a slow return to democracy, which was completed during the 1980s.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Civilians returned to power in 1985 when José Sarney assumed the presidency.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] He became unpopular during his tenure through failure to control the economic crisis and hyperinflation he inherited from the military regime.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Sarney's unsuccessful government led to the election in 1989 of the almost-unknown Fernando Collor, who was subsequently impeached by the National Congress in 1992.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Collor was succeeded by his vice-president, Itamar Franco, who appointed Fernando Henrique Cardoso as Minister of Finance.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 1994, Cardoso devised a highly successful Plano Real that, after decades of failed economic plans made by previous governments attempting to curb hyperinflation, finally stabilized the Brazilian economy.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Cardoso won the 1994 election, and again in 1998.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The peaceful transition of power from Cardoso to his main opposition leader, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva (elected in 2002 and re-elected in 2006), was seen as proof that Brazil had achieved a long-sought political stability.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Rousseff was impeached by the Brazilian Congress in 2016, halfway into her second term, and replaced by her vice-president Michel Temer, who assumed full presidential powers after Rousseff's impeachment was accepted on 31 August.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Large street protests for and against her took place during the impeachment process.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The charges against her were fueled by political and economic crises along with evidence of involvement with politicians from all the primary political parties.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 2017, the Supreme Court requested the investigation of 71 Brazilian lawmakers and nine ministers of President Michel Temer's cabinet who were allegedly linked to the Petrobras corruption scandal.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] President Temer himself was also accused of corruption.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the fiercely contested 2018 elections, the controversial conservative candidate Jair Bolsonaro of the Social Liberal Party (PSL) was elected president, winning in the second round against Fernando Haddad, of the Workers Party (PT), with the support of 55.13% of the valid votes.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the early 2020s, Brazil became one of the hardest hit countries during the COVID-19 pandemic, receiving the second-highest death toll worldwide after the United States.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In May 2021, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva stated that he would run for a third term in the 2022 Brazilian general election against Bolsonaro.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In October 2022, Lula was in first place in the first round, with 48.43% of the support from the electorate, and received 50.90% of the votes in the second round.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] On 8 January 2023, a week after Lula's inauguration, a mob of Bolsonaro's supporters attacked Brazil's federal government buildings in the capital, Brasília, after several weeks of unrest.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil occupies nearly half of the land area of South America (47.7%), including a large area along its eastern coast and much of the continent's interior.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It borders Uruguay to the south; Argentina and Paraguay to the southwest; Bolivia and Peru to the west; Colombia to the northwest; and Venezuela, Guyana, Suriname, and France (French overseas region of French Guiana) to the north.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It shares a border with every South American country except Ecuador and Chile.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Brazilian territory also encompasses a number of oceanic archipelagos, such as Fernando de Noronha, Rocas Atoll, Saint Peter and Saint Paul Archipelago, and the islands of Trindade and Martim Vaz.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Its size, relief, climate, and natural resources make Brazil geographically diverse.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Including its Atlantic islands, Brazil lies between latitudes 6°N and 34°S, and longitudes 28° and 74°W.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil is the fifth largest country in the world, and third largest in the Americas, with a total area of 8,515,767.049 km2 (3,287,956 sq mi), including 55,455 km2 (21,411 sq mi) of water.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil is the only country in the world that has the equator and the Tropic of Capricorn running through it.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It spans four time zones; from UTC−5 comprising the state of Acre and the westernmost portion of Amazonas, to UTC−4 in the western states, to UTC−3 in the eastern states (the national time) and UTC−2 in the Atlantic islands.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The climate of Brazil comprises a wide range of weather conditions across a large area and varied topography, but most of the country is tropical.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] According to the Köppen system, Brazil hosts six major climatic subtypes: desert, equatorial, tropical, semiarid, oceanic and subtropical.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The different climatic conditions produce environments ranging from equatorial rainforests in the north and semiarid deserts in the northeast, to temperate coniferous forests in the south and tropical savannas in central Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In Brazil, forest cover is around 59% of the total land area, equivalent to 496,619,600 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 588,898,000 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 485,396,000 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 11,223,600 hectares (ha).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 44% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 30% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] For 2015, 56% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership and 44% private ownership.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Many regions have starkly different microclimates.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] An equatorial climate characterizes much of northern Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] There is no real dry season, but there are some variations in the period of the year when most rain falls.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Temperatures average 25 °C (77 °F), with more significant temperature variation between night and day than between seasons.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Over central Brazil, rainfall is more seasonal, characteristic of a savanna climate.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] This region is as extensive as the Amazon basin but has a very different climate as it lies farther south at a higher altitude.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the interior northeast, seasonal rainfall is even more extreme.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] South of Bahia, near the coasts, and more southerly most of the state of São Paulo, the distribution of rainfall changes, with rain falling throughout the year.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The south enjoys subtropical conditions, with cool winters and average annual temperatures not exceeding 18 °C (64.4 °F); winter frosts and snowfall are not rare in the highest areas.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The semiarid climatic region generally receives less than 800 millimeters (31.5 in) of rain, most of which generally falls in a period of three to five months of the year and occasionally less than this, creating long periods of drought.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's 1877–78 *Grande Seca* (Great Drought), the worst in Brazil's history, caused approximately half a million deaths.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] A similarly devastating drought occurred in 1915.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 2024, for the first time, "a drought has covered all the way from the North to the country's Southeast".
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It is the strongest drought in Brazil since the beginning of measurement in the 1950s, covering almost 60% of the country's territory.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The drought is linked to deforestation and climate change.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Climate change in Brazil is causing higher temperatures and longer-lasting heatwaves, changing precipitation patterns, more intense wildfires and heightened fire risk.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's hydropower, agriculture and urban water supplies will be affected.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's rainforests, and the Amazon, are particularly at risk to climate change.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] At worst, large areas of the Amazon River basin could turn into savannah, with severe consequences for global climate and local livelihoods.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Extreme weather events like droughts and flash floods are causing annual losses of around R$13 billion (US$2.6 billion), equivalent to 0.1% of the country's 2022 GDP.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Climate impacts could exacerbate poverty.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's greenhouse gas emissions per person are higher than the global average, and Brazil is among the top 10 highest emitting countries.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Greenhouse gas emissions by Brazil are over 4% of the annual world total.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 2026 the Brazilian government has launched a National Climate Change Plan which should cut greenhouse gas emissions by 59% - 67% by 2035, and make the country carbon neutral by 2050.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil hosted the 2025 United Nations Climate Change Conference, in which it launched the Global carbon market coalition immediately joined by 11 countries including Brazil, China, the European Union, United Kingdom.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] According to some calculations, a global carbon market can speed up emission reduction seven-fold.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazilian topography is also diverse and includes hills, mountains, plains, highlands, and scrublands.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Much of the terrain lies between 200 meters (660 ft) and 800 meters (2,600 ft) in elevation.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The main upland area occupies most of the southern half of the country.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The northwestern parts of the plateau consist of broad, rolling terrain broken by low, rounded hills.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The southeastern section is more rugged, with a complex mass of ridges and mountain ranges reaching elevations of up to 1,200 meters (3,900 ft).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] These ranges include the Mantiqueira and Espinhaço mountains and the Serra do Mar.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the north, the Guiana Highlands form a major drainage divide, separating rivers that flow south into the Amazon Basin from rivers that empty into the Orinoco River system, in Venezuela, to the north.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The highest point in Brazil is the Pico da Neblina at 2,994 meters (9,823 ft), and the lowest is the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil has a dense and complex system of rivers, one of the world's most extensive, with eight major drainage basins, all of which drain into the Atlantic.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Major rivers include the Amazon (the world's largest in terms of water volume), the Paraná and its major tributary the Iguaçu (which includes the Iguazu Falls), the Negro, São Francisco, Xingu, Madeira and Tapajós rivers.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The wildlife of Brazil comprises all naturally occurring animals, plants, and fungi in the South American country.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Home to 60% of the Amazon rainforest, which accounts for approximately one-tenth of all species in the world, Brazil is considered to have the greatest biodiversity of any country on the planet, containing over 70% of all animal and plant species catalogued.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil has the most known species of plants (55,000), freshwater fish (3,000) and mammals (over 689).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It also ranks third on the list of countries with the most bird species (1,832) and second with the most reptile species (744).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The number of fungal species is unknown but is large.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil is second only to Indonesia as the country with the most endemic species.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's large territory comprises different ecosystems, such as the Amazon rainforest, recognized as having the greatest biological diversity in the world, with the Atlantic Forest and the Cerrado sustaining the greatest biodiversity.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In the south, the Araucaria moist forests grow under temperate conditions.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The rich wildlife of Brazil reflects the variety of natural habitats.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Scientists estimate that the total number of plant and animal species in Brazil could approach four million, mostly invertebrates.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Larger mammals include carnivores pumas, jaguars, ocelots, rare bush dogs, and foxes, and herbivores peccaries, tapirs, anteaters, sloths, opossums and armadillos.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Deer are plentiful in the south, and many species of New World monkeys are found in the northern rainforests.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] More than one-fifth of the Amazon rainforest in Brazil has been completely destroyed, and more than 70 mammals are endangered.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The threat of extinction comes from several sources, including deforestation and poaching.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Extinction is even more problematic in the Atlantic Forest, where nearly 93% of the forest has been cleared.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Of the 202 endangered animals in Brazil, 171 are in the Atlantic Forest.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Amazon rainforest has been under direct threat of deforestation since the 1970s because of rapid economic and demographic expansion.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Extensive legal and illegal logging destroy forests the size of a small country per year, and with it a diverse series of species through habitat destruction and habitat fragmentation.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Since 1970, over 600,000 square kilometers (230,000 sq mi) of the Amazon rainforest have been cleared by logging.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 2017, preserved native vegetation occupied 61% of the Brazilian territory.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Agriculture occupied only 8% of the national territory and pastures 19.7%.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] For comparison, in 2019, although 43% of the entire European continent has forests, only 3% of the total forest area in Europe is of native forest.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil has a strong interest in conservation, as its agriculture sector directly depends on its forests.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The form of government is a democratic federative republic, with a presidential system, as decided in a 1993 referendum.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The president is both head of state and head of government of the Union and is elected for a four-year term, with the possibility of re-election for a second successive term.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The current president is Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The president appoints the Ministers of State, who form the cabinet and assist in government.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Legislative houses in each political entity are the main source of law in Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The National Congress is the federation's bicameral legislature, consisting of the Chamber of Deputies and the Federal Senate.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Senate represents the 26 states and the Federal District.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Each state and the Federal District has a representation of three senators, who are elected by popular ballot for a term of eight years.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Chamber of Deputies represents the people of each state, and its members are elected for a four-year term by a system of proportional representation.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Judiciary authorities exercise jurisdictional duties almost exclusively.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Brazil performs in the mid to high range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in inclusive suffrage, freedom of religion, and civic engagement.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 2021, the Economist Intelligence Unit's Democracy Index categorized Brazil as a "flawed democracy", ranking 46th in the report, and Freedom House classified it as a free country at *Freedom in the World* report.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] According to the Regimes of the World classification Brazil was an electoral democracy in year 2024.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The political-administrative organization of the Federative Republic of Brazil comprises the Union, the states, the Federal District, and the municipalities.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Union, the states, the Federal District, and the municipalities, are the "spheres of government".
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The federation is set on five fundamental principles: sovereignty, citizenship, dignity of human beings, the social values of labor and freedom of enterprise, and political pluralism.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The classic tripartite branches of government (executive, legislative and judicial under a checks and balances system) are formally established by the constitution.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The executive and legislative are organized independently in all three spheres of government, while the judiciary is organized only at the federal and state and Federal District spheres.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] All members of the executive and legislative branches are directly elected.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] For most of its democratic history, Brazil has had a multi-party system, with proportional representation.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Voting is compulsory for the literate between 18 and 70 years old and optional for illiterates and those between 16 and 18 or beyond 70.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The country has around 30 registered political parties.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Twenty political parties are represented in Congress.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It is common for politicians to switch parties, and thus the proportion of congressional seats held by particular parties changes regularly.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazilian law is based on the civil law legal system and civil law concepts prevail over common law practice.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Most of Brazilian law is codified, although non-codified statutes also represent a substantial part, playing a complementary role.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Court decisions set out interpretive guidelines; however, they are seldom binding on other specific cases.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Doctrinal works and the works of academic jurists have strong influence in law creation and in law cases.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Judges and other judicial officials are appointed after passing entry exams.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The legal system is based on the Federal Constitution, promulgated on 5 October 1988, and the fundamental law of Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] All other legislation and court decisions must conform to its rules.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] As of July 2022, there have been 124 amendments.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The highest court is the Supreme Federal Court.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] States have their own constitutions, which must not contradict the Federal Constitution.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Municipalities and the Federal District have "organic laws" (*leis orgânicas*), which act in a similar way to constitutions.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Legislative entities are the main source of statutes, although in certain matters judiciary and executive bodies may enact legal norms.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Jurisdiction is administered by the judiciary entities, although in rare situations the Federal Constitution allows the Federal Senate to pass on legal judgments.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] There are also specialized military, labor and electoral courts.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil is a federation composed of 26 states, one federal district, and the 5,571 municipalities.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] States have autonomous administrations, collect their own taxes and receive a share of taxes collected by the Federal government.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] They have a governor and a unicameral legislative body elected directly by their voters.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] They also have independent Courts of Law for common justice.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] States have the ability to create their own laws and establish their own constitutions but criminal and civil laws can be voted by only the federal bicameral Congress and are uniform throughout the country.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Municipalities, as the states, have autonomous administrations, collect their own taxes and receive a share of taxes collected by the federal and state government.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Each has an elected mayor and legislative body, but no separate Court of Law.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Indeed, a Court of Law organized by the state can encompass many municipalities in a single justice administrative division called *comarca*.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's constitution also provides for the creation of federal territories, which are administrative divisions directly controlled by the federal government.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] However, there are currently no federal territories in the country, as the 1988 constitution abolished the last three: Amapá and Roraima (which gained statehood) and Fernando de Noronha, which became a state district of Pernambuco.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] According to the constitution, the president has ultimate authority over foreign policy, while Congress is tasked with reviewing and considering all diplomatic nominations and international treaties, as well as legislation relating to Brazilian foreign policy.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's foreign policy is a by-product of the country's position as a regional power in Latin America, a leader among developing countries, and an emerging world power.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazilian foreign policy has generally been based on the principles of multilateralism, peaceful dispute settlement, and non-intervention in the affairs of other countries.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil is a founding member state of the Community of Portuguese Language Countries (CPLP), also known as the Lusophone Commonwealth, an international organization and political association of Lusophone nations.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] An increasingly well-developed tool of Brazil's foreign policy is providing aid as a donor to other developing countries.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil does not just use its growing economic strength to provide financial aid, but it also provides high levels of expertise and most importantly of all, a quiet non-confrontational diplomacy to improve governance levels.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Total aid is estimated to be around $1 billion per year.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In addition, Brazil already managed a peacekeeping mission in Haiti ($350 million) and makes in-kind contributions to the World Food Programme ($300 million).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The scale of this aid places it on par with China and India.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Brazilian South-South aid has been described as a "global model in waiting".
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The armed forces of Brazil are the largest in Latin America by active personnel and the largest in terms of military equipment.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It consists of the Brazilian Army (including the Army Aviation Command), the Brazilian Navy (including the Marine Corps and Naval Aviation) and the Brazilian Air Force.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's conscription policy gives it one of the world's largest military forces, estimated at more than 1.6 million reservists annually.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The Air Force is the largest in Latin America and has about 700 crewed aircraft in service and effective about 67,000 personnel.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Numbering close to 236,000 active personnel, the Brazilian Army has the largest number of armored vehicles in South America, including armored transports and tanks.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The states' Military Police and the Military Firefighters Corps are designated as auxiliary forces of the army by the constitution, but are under the control of each state's governor.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil's navy once operated some of the most powerful warships in the world with the two *Minas Geraes*-class dreadnoughts, sparking a naval arms race between Argentina, Brazil, and Chile.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Today, it is a green water force and has a group of specialized elite in retaking ships and naval facilities, GRUMEC, unit specially trained to protect Brazilian oil platforms along its coast.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] As of 2022, it is the only navy in Latin America that operates a helicopter carrier, NAM *Atlântico* and one of twelve navies in the world to operate or have one under construction.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In Brazil, the constitution establishes six different police agencies for law enforcement: Federal Police Department, Federal Highway Police, Federal Railroad Police, Federal, District and State Penal Police (included by the Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] 104, of 2019), Military Police and Civil Police.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Of these, the former three are affiliated with federal authorities, the latter two are subordinate to state governments and the Penal Police can be subordinated to the federal or state/district government.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] All police forces are overseen by the executive branch of the federal or state governments.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The National Public Security Force also can act in public disorder situations arising anywhere in the country.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The country has high levels of violent crime, such as gun violence and homicides.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] In 2022, the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) estimated an intentional homicide rate of 21.1 per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The number considered acceptable by the World Health Organization (WHO) is about 10 homicides per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] While in São Paulo the homicide rate registered in 2025 was 5.4 per 100,000 inhabitants, in Ceará it was 32.6 per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The national homicide rate for 2025 was 16 per 100,000 inhabitants, the lowest in over a decade.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Brazil also has high levels of incarceration.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] It had the third largest prison population in the world of approximately 909,067 prisoners in 2024, which put it only behind the United States (1,808,100) and China (1,690,000).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The high number of prisoners eventually overloaded the Brazilian prison system, leading to a shortfall of about 200,000 accommodations.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Human rights in Brazil include the right to life and freedom of speech; and condemnation of slavery and torture.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The nation ratified the American Convention on Human Rights.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] The 2017 Freedom in the World report by Freedom House gives Brazil a score of "2" for both political rights and civil liberties; "1" represents the most free, and "7", the least.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] According to UNESCO, "Brazil promotes a vast array of actions for the advancement and defense of human rights, even though it faces enormous social and economic inequalities".
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p01] Same-sex couples in Brazil have held nationwide marriage rights since May 2013.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is a developing country with an upper-middle income mixed market economy that is rich in natural resources.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] It has the largest national economy in Latin America, the tenth largest economy in the world by nominal GDP, and the eighth largest by PPP.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] After rapid growth in preceding decades, Brazil entered a recession in 2014 amid a political corruption scandal and nationwide protests; in 2024, the economy began showing consistent significant growth.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil has a labor force of roughly 100 million, which is the world's fifth largest.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Its foreign exchange reserves are the tenth-highest in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The B3 in São Paulo is the largest stock exchange of Latin America by market capitalization.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Roughly one-fifth of Brazilians live in poverty: about 3.8% of the total population lives at $3.00 a day, while about 23% live at $8.30 a day.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil's economy suffers from endemic corruption and high income inequality.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The Brazilian real is the national currency.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil's diversified economy includes agriculture, industry and a wide range of services.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The large service sector accounts for about 72.7% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (20.7%), while the agriculture sector is by far the smallest, making up 6.6% of total GDP.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is one of the largest producers of various agricultural commodities, and also has a large cooperative sector that provides 50% of the food in the country.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Regarding livestock, it is one of the five largest producers of chicken meat, beef, pork and cow's milk in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In the mining sector, Brazil is among the largest producers of iron ore, copper, gold, bauxite, manganese, tin, niobium, and nickel.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In terms of precious stones, Brazil is the world's largest producer of amethyst, topaz, agate and one of the main producers of tourmaline, emerald, aquamarine, garnet and opal.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The country is a major exporter of soy, iron ore, pulp (cellulose), maize, beef, chicken meat, soybean meal, sugar, coffee, tobacco, cotton, orange juice, footwear, airplanes, cars, vehicle parts, gold, ethanol and semi-finished iron, among other products.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is the world's 24th-largest exporter and 26th-largest importer as of 2021.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] China is its largest trading partner, accounting for 32% of the total trade.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Other large trading partners include the United States, Argentina, the Netherlands and Canada.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Its automotive industry is the eighth-largest in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In the food industry, Brazil was the second-largest exporter of processed foods in the world in 2019.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The country was the second-largest producer of pulp in the world and the eighth-largest producer of paper in 2016.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In the footwear industry, Brazil was the fourth-largest producer in 2019.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] It was also the ninth-largest producer of steel in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In 2018, the chemical industry of Brazil was the eighth-largest in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Although it was among the five largest world producers in 2013, Brazil's textile industry is very little integrated into world trade.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The tertiary sector (trade and services) represented 75.8% of the country's GDP in 2018, according to the IBGE.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The service sector was responsible for 60% of GDP and trade for 13%.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] It covers commerce, transport, education, social and health services, research and development, sports activities, etc.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Micro and small businesses represent 30% of the country's GDP.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In the commercial sector they represent 53% of the GDP within the activities of the sector.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Natural areas are its most popular tourism product, a combination of ecotourism with leisure and recreation, mainly sun and beach, and adventure travel, as well as cultural tourism.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Among the most popular destinations are the Amazon Rainforest, beaches and dunes in the Northeast Region, the Pantanal in the Center-West Region, beaches at Rio de Janeiro and Santa Catarina, cultural tourism in Minas Gerais and business trips to São Paulo.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Domestic tourism is a key market segment for the tourism industry in Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In 2005, 51 million Brazilian nationals made ten times more trips than foreign tourists and spent five times more money than their international counterparts.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The main destination states in 2023 were São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Rio Grande do Sul.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The main source of tourists for the entire country is São Paulo state.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In terms of tourism revenues, the top earners by state were São Paulo and Bahia.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] For 2005, the three main trip purposes were visiting friends and family (53.1%), sun and beach (40.8%), and cultural tourism (12.5%).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Technological research in Brazil is largely carried out in public universities and research institutes, with the majority of funding for basic research coming from various government agencies.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil's most esteemed technological hubs are the Oswaldo Cruz Institute, the Butantan Institute, the Air Force's Aerospace Technical Center, the Brazilian Agricultural Research Corporation and the National Institute for Space Research.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The Brazilian Space Agency has the most developed space program in Latin America, with significant capabilities in launch vehicles, launch sites, and satellite manufacturing.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is the only country in the Southern Hemisphere involved in the International Space Station (ISS).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The country also develops submarines and is the world's third largest aircraft producer, primarily through Embraer.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The country is also a pioneer in the search for oil in deep water, from where it extracts 73% of its reserves.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Uranium is enriched at the Resende Nuclear Fuel Factory, mostly for research purposes (as Brazil obtains 88% of its electricity from hydroelectricity), and the country's first nuclear submarine is expected to launch in 2029.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is one of the three countries in Latin America with an operational Synchrotron Laboratory (a research facility on physics, chemistry, material science and life sciences), and the only Latin American country with a domestic fabrication plant, the CEITEC.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] According to the Global Information Technology Report 2009–2010 of the World Economic Forum, Brazil is the world's 61st largest developer of information technology.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil ranked 52nd in the Global Innovation Index in 2025, up from 66th in 2019.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Among the most renowned Brazilian inventors are priests Bartolomeu de Gusmão, Landell de Moura and Francisco João de Azevedo, besides Alberto Santos-Dumont, Evaristo Conrado Engelberg, Manuel Dias de Abreu, Andreas Pavel and Nélio José Nicolai.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is the world's eleventh-largest energy consumer.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Much of its energy comes from renewable sources, particularly hydroelectricity and ethanol; the Itaipu Dam is the world's largest hydroelectric plant by energy generation, and the country has other large plants such as Belo Monte and Tucuruí.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The first car with an ethanol engine was produced in 1978 and the first airplane engine running on ethanol in 2005.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] At the end of 2021, Brazil ranked second in the world by installed hydroelectric power (109.4 GW) and biomass (15.8 GW), seventh in installed wind power (21.1 GW) and 14th in installed solar power (13.0 GW)—on track to also become one of the top 10 in the world in solar energy.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] At the end of 2024, Brazil was the fourth largest producer of wind energy in the world (107.8 TWh), behind only China, the United States and Germany, and the world's fifth largest producer of solar energy (74.7 TWh).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Overall, Brazil ranks third globally in renewable electricity production, after China and the United States, accounting for 7% of the global total.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The Brazilian energy matrix is characterized by a higher degree of renewable energy than the global average; in 2022, the world energy matrix was only 14% renewable energy, compared to 45% in Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Petroleum and oil products made up 34.3% of the country's matrix; sugar cane derivatives, 18%; hydraulic energy, 12.4%; natural gas, 12.2%; firewood and charcoal, 8.8%; varied renewable energies, 7%; mineral coal, 5.3%; nuclear, 1.4%, and other non-renewable energies, 0.6%.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Similarly, the vast majority of Brazilian electricity is derived from renewable sources: 83% compared to 25% worldwide.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The leading sources are hydraulic energy at 64.9%; biomass, 8.4%; wind, 8.6%; solar, 1%; natural gas, 9.3%; oil products, 2%; nuclear, 2.5%; and coal and derivatives, 3.3%.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil has the largest electricity sector in Latin America; its capacity at the end of 2021 was 181,532 MW.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The Brazilian government has embarked on a program over the decades to reduce dependence on imported oil, which previously accounted for more than 70% of the country's oil needs.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil became self-sufficient in oil in 2006–2007.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] By the end of 2021, the country was the seventh largest oil producer in the world, with an average of nearly three million barrels per day, and became an exporter of the product.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazilian roads are the primary carriers of freight and passenger traffic.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The road system totaled 2,000,000 km (1,242,742 mi) in 2023, ranking fourth largest by size globally.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil's railway system has been declining since 1945, when emphasis shifted to highway construction.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The country's total railway track length was 30,576 km (18,999 mi) in 2015, as compared with 31,848 km (19,789 mi) in 1970, making it the ninth largest network in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Most of the railway system belonged to the Federal Railroad Network Corporation (RFFSA), which was privatized in 2007.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The São Paulo Metro began operating on 14 September 1974 as the first underground transit system in Brazil.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] There are over 4,900 airports and airfields in Brazil, second only to the United States.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] São Paulo–Guarulhos International Airport, near São Paulo, is the largest and busiest airport with nearly 43 million passengers annually, while handling the vast majority of commercial traffic for the country.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] For freight transport, waterways are of importance.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The industrial zones of Manaus can be reached only by means of the Solimões–Amazonas waterway (3,250 kilometers or 2,020 miles in length, with a minimum depth of six meters or 20 feet).
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The country also has 50,000 kilometers (31,000 miles) of waterways.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Coastal shipping links widely separated parts of the country.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Bolivia and Paraguay have been given free ports at Santos.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Of the 36 deep-water ports, Santos, Itajaí, Rio Grande, Paranaguá, Rio de Janeiro, Sepetiba, Vitória, Suape, Manaus and São Francisco do Sul are the most important.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Bulk carriers have to wait up to 18 days before being serviced; container ships take 36.3 hours on average.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] According to the latest official projection, Brazil's estimated population was 213,421,037 on 1 July 2025—an increase from the figure of 203 million reported by the 2022 census.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The population of Brazil, as recorded by the 2008 PNAD, was approximately 190 million (22.31 inhabitants per square kilometer or 57.8/sq mi), with a ratio of men to women of 0.95:1 and 83.75% of the population defined as urban.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The population is heavily concentrated in the Southeast (89 million inhabitants) and Northeast (54.6 million inhabitants), while the two most extensive regions, the Center-West and the North, which together make up 64.12% of Brazilian territory, have a total of only 33.8 million inhabitants.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The first census in Brazil was carried out in 1872 and recorded a population of 9,930,478.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] From 1880 to 1930, four million Europeans arrived.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil's population increased significantly between 1940 and 1970, because of a decline in the mortality rate, even though the birth rate underwent a slight decline.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In the 1940s the annual population growth rate was 2.4%, rising to 3.0% in the 1950s and remaining at 2.9% in the 1960s, as life expectancy rose from 44 to 54 years and to 72.6 years in 2007.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] It has been steadily falling since the 1960s, from 3.04% per year between 1950 and 1960 to 1.05% in 2008 and is expected to fall to a negative value of –0.29% by 2050 thus completing the demographic transition.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In 2022, the illiteracy rate was roughly 7%, a significant decline from 11.48% in 2008.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] By comparison, in 1940, more than half the population (54%) was illiterate.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] According to IBGE (Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics) urban areas already concentrate 84.35% of the population, while the Southeast region remains the most populated one, with over 80 million inhabitants.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The largest urban agglomerations in Brazil are São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Belo Horizonte—all in the Southeastern Region—with 21.1, 12.3, and 5.1 million inhabitants respectively.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The majority of state capitals are the largest cities in their states, except for Vitória, the capital of Espírito Santo, and Florianópolis, the capital of Santa Catarina.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] From the 19th century, Brazil opened its borders to immigration.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] About five million people from over 60 countries migrated to Brazil between 1808 and 1972, most of them of Portuguese, Italian, Spanish, German, English, Ukrainian, Polish, Jewish, African, Armenian, Russian, Chinese, Japanese, Korean and Arab origin.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil has the second-largest Jewish community in Latin America after Argentina making up 0.06% of its population.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Outside of the Arab world, Brazil also has the largest population of Arab ancestry in the world, with 15–20 million people.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] According to Brazil's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Brazil is home to a Lebanese diaspora of 7-10 million, surpassing the population of Lebanese individuals residing in Lebanon.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazilian society is more markedly divided by social class lines, although a high income disparity is found between race groups, so racism and classism often overlap.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Higher percents of Blacks, mulattoes and tri-racials can be found in the eastern coast of the Northeastern region from Bahia to Paraíba and also in northern Maranhão, southern Minas Gerais and eastern Rio de Janeiro.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] People of considerable Amerindian ancestry form the majority of the population in the Northern, Northeastern and Center-Western regions.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In 2007, the National Indian Foundation estimated that Brazil has 67 different uncontacted tribes, up from their estimate of 40 in 2005.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is believed to have the largest number of uncontacted peoples in the world.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] The official language of Brazil is Portuguese (Article 13 of the Constitution of the Federal Republic of Brazil), which almost all of the population speaks and is virtually the only language used in newspapers, radio, television, and for business and administrative purposes.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil is the only Portuguese-speaking nation in the Americas, making the language an important part of Brazilian national identity and giving it a national culture distinct from those of its Spanish-speaking neighbors.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] These differences are comparable to those between American and British English.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] LIBRAS teachers, instructors and translators are recognized professionals.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Schools and health services must provide access ("inclusion") to deaf people.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Minority languages are spoken throughout the nation.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] One hundred and eighty Amerindian languages are spoken in remote areas and a significant number of other languages are spoken by immigrants and their descendants.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] In the municipality of São Gabriel da Cachoeira, Nheengatu (a currently endangered creole language that, together with its southern relative língua geral paulista, once was a major lingua franca in Brazil), Baniwa and Tucano languages had been granted co-official status with Portuguese.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Talian is officially a historic heritage of Rio Grande do Sul, and two German dialects possess co-official status in a few municipalities.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Italian is also recognized as "ethnic language" in Santa Teresa and Vila Velha, in the state of Espírito Santo.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Christianity is the country's predominant faith, with Catholicism being its largest denomination.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] Brazil has the world's largest Catholic population.
[src:dodge-charger/brazil-p02] According to the 2022 demographic census (the PNAD survey does not inquire about religion), 56.75% of the population followed Catholicism; 26.85% Protestantism; 1.84% Kardecist spiritism; 5.06% other religions, undeclared or undetermined; while 9.28% had no religion.
